                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, Sept. 21 : India today rejected resolutions on Jammu and Kashmir passed by Pakistans Senate and National Assembly.          
	The resolutions had appealed to the world community to take notice of Indian repression in occupied Kashmir.           
	Delhi said the move had no locus standi as Kashmir was Indias internal matter. It said Islamabads raised pitch on Kashmir was consistent with its past record of raking up the Kashmir issue to coincide with the UN General Assembly session.           dian external affairs minister S.M. Krishna and his Pakistani counterpart Shah Mahmood Qureshi are in New York to attend the UN General Assembly session.                   
	 Calcutta: Calcutta High Court on Tuesday issued an interim stay on a Central Administrative Tribunal order, which had set aside the promotions of four inspectors-general of police, one of them in charge of the chief ministers security. The promotions had been set aside on the ground that they had superseded two IPS officers.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): A suspected Pakistani spy, who has been staying here for the past one year allegedly doing recce of army installations, has been arrested. Police say they have recovered confidential documents from him.                  
	 Raipur (PTI): A close aide of Maoist leader Gudsa Usendi was arrested from Durg district in Chhattisgarh on Monday. Radheshyam Giri assisted Maoists with basic amenities to carry out their operations, police said.                  
	 Thiruvananthapuram (PTI): The Kerala government has asked the Centre to take stringent action, including a ban on Sikkim and Bhutan paper lotteries, in the wake of evidence that promoters of these lotteries were violating rules. It was found that the press where the lottery tickets and papers were printed did not have the security press recognition.
                                                                                                                                              
